From Soup: 39 At the wall surfaces we also enforce no-slip boundary conditions using a stochastic reflection method but additionally we fill the wall cells with n s a 3 − N ξ “ghost” particles during the collision step ( n s a 3 is the average number of solvent particles in the collision cell ), because due to the random shift partially occupied boundary collision cells occur. 20 The velocities of the “ghost” particles are drawn from a Maxwell–Boltzmann distribution with zero mean and variance k B T .
 ###### 
From cou.: 40 This thermostat acts locally and is unbiased with respect to the flow field and hence does not destroy the hydrodynamic behaviour, see ref. 18.
From Soup: 40 We employed the parameters Δ t = 0.2 τ , α = 3π/4, n s a 3 = 5 with . With these parameters the total solvent kinematic viscosity is ν = η / ρ ≈ 0.5 a 2 / τ ( ρ = mn s is the mass density and η the dynamic viscosity). 21 For the colloids we use M = 167 m , hard core diameter σ = 4 a and δ t = Δ t /4. We calculate the diffusion constant in a bulk simulation from the integral of the velocity autocorrelation function and obtain D = 0.013 a 2 / t 0. 17 With these parameters we achieve the hierarchy of time scales for a colloidal particle Δ t = 0.2 τ < τ c = 1.5 τ < τ B = 2.2 τ < τ ν = 8 τ < τ D = 307 τ , see ref. 22 . Here τ c is the time a sound wave needs to propagate over one colloidal radius (the speed of sound is ), τ B is the time the velocity of a colloid is correlated and τ ν is the time over which the solvent momentum diffuses over one colloidal radius. We performed simulations up to Pe max = 4.8 which correspond to a maximal Reynolds number of Re max = D / νPe max ≈ 0.125 < 1, such that inertial effects are negligible. To avoid compressibility effects we also ensure that the Mach number is smaller than unity, Ma max = 2 D /( σc ) Pe max = 0.024 ≪ 1. With these values of the hydrodynamic numbers and the hierarchy of time scales we are sure that a comparison with a real physical system is reasonable.
 ###### 
From cou.: 41 For a small mean free path the same set of particles interact over several Δt with each other before leaving this cell and hence they remain correlated over several Δt. If one imposes a flow field the degree of correlation and therefore the transport coefficients depends on the magnitude of the flow field. The violated Galilean invariance can be restored if all particle positions are shifted by a random vector before the collision step.19
From Soup: 41 The system we consider contains N = 15 048 hard sphere particles and N s = 14 274 843 solvent particles in a box of L / σ = 18 and L y / σ = L z / σ = 54. We start our simulation with a fully equilibrated system under the influence of a constant force in the x -direction, i.e. particles have collected and settled at the top of the box. Then at time t = 0 we instantaneously reverse the direction of the force and monitor the evolution of the system until all particles have sedimented to the bottom.
 ###### 
From cou.: 42 At the wall surfaces we also enforce no-slip boundary conditions using a stochastic reflection method but additionally we fill the wall cells with nsa3 − Nξ “ghost” particles during the collision step (nsa3 is the average number of solvent particles in the collision cell), because due to the random shift partially occupied boundary collision cells occur.20 The velocities of the “ghost” particles are drawn from a Maxwell–Boltzmann distribution with zero mean and variance kBT.
From Soup: 42 We compare our simulation to single-particle level confocal microscopy experiments with sterically stabilised polymethylmethacrylate colloids. The value of the Peclet number can be adjusted by variation of the density mismatch between colloid and solvent mass density. Prior equilibration was achieved by placing the suspension overnight such that it sedimented across a thin (typically 50 µm) capillary. The capillary was then inverted, and the evolution under sedimentation was followed. More details of the experiment are described in ref. 23,24 .
