From cou.: 43 We employed the parameters Δt = 0.2τ, α = 3π/4, nsa3 = 5 with . With these parameters the total solvent kinematic viscosity is ν = η/ρ ≈ 0.5a2/τ (ρ = mns is the mass density and η the dynamic viscosity).21 For the colloids we use M = 167m, hard core diameter σ = 4a and δt = Δt/4. We calculate the diffusion constant in a bulk simulation from the integral of the velocity autocorrelation function and obtain D = 0.013a2/t0.17 With these parameters we achieve the hierarchy of time scales for a colloidal particle Δt = 0.2τ < τc = 1.5τ < τB = 2.2τ < τν = 8τ < τD = 307τ, see ref. 22. Here τc is the time a sound wave needs to propagate over one colloidal radius (the speed of sound is ), τB is the time the velocity of a colloid is correlated and τν is the time over which the solvent momentum diffuses over one colloidal radius. We performed simulations up to Pemax = 4.8 which correspond to a maximal Reynolds number of Remax = D/νPemax ≈ 0.125 < 1, such that inertial effects are negligible. To avoid compressibility effects we also ensure that the Mach number is smaller than unity, Mamax = 2D/(σc)Pemax = 0.024 ≪ 1. With these values of the hydrodynamic numbers and the hierarchy of time scales we are sure that a comparison with a real physical system is reasonable.
From Soup: 43 A situation where a layer of a heavy fluid is on top of a lighter one is clearly mechanically unstable, i.e. the system is inclined to invert. During this process the initially flat interface starts to develop perturbations with a characteristic wavelength λ = 2π/ k , where k is a wave number.
